title: For Trade:  Taurus PT22 Nickel finish
postcontent:
The PT22 is a .22LR semi-automatic pistol produced by Taurus and features an 8+1 round capacity magazine.. The PT22 is a steel frame and slide, manufactured in the USA. It has a spur-less hammer, and a long but smooth double action only (DAO) trigger. 
Something these little Taurus pistols have been praised for is the tip-up barrel design. What looks something like a slide release on the left side of the gun is actually a barrel release. Press it forward and the rear of the barrel pops up for loading a round directly into the chamber. There is no need to rack the slide, which is a benefit to those who, because of arthritis or other hand weakness, are unable to operate conventional auto pistols. Very accurate for its size with almost no felt recoil.

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  CZ 75 P-01 9mm 91199
postcontent: The P-01 9mm (accompanied by the P-06 in .40 S&W) was designed for LE and Military duty, but its compact size and the reduced weight due to its forged alloy frame made it ideal for discrete carry as well. Equipped with a decocker, the P-01 provides convenience for those who prefer hammer-down carry. The P-01 was the first CZ model to benefit from updated manufacturing technology at CZ’s Uhersky Brod factory. The components of the P-01/P-06 are completely interchangable with every other P-01/P-06, with no individual fitting required. This required some very careful re-design so that the reliability and accuracy were not impaired. Since the time of its introduction (designed in 2001, NATO-approved in 2003) the production upgrades have been rolled out to most of the CZ 75 family and several new rifle models as well. The 1913 accessory rail easily accepts any of the industry-standard lights and lasers to assist low-light use. After 3 years of some of the most aggressive small arms testing ever, the CZ P-01 won the honor of replacing the CZ 75s previously used by the Czech National Police. Reliability: The U.S. Army “Mean Rounds Between Failure” (MRBF) requirement is 495 rounds for 9mm pistols. During testing of the CZ P-01, the average number of stoppages was only 7 per 15,000 rounds fired. This is a .05% failure rate or an MRBF of 2142! For many years, the P-01 carried an NSN engraved on its frame, making it the first NATO-spec pistol ever available to the public. Recently, the factory decided to upgrade the slide stop spring which in turn means the current models may not carry the NSN.

title: For Sale:  CZ52 Pistol Set - Early Gray Phosphate Finish VERY NICE
postcontent:
This CZ52 pistol is one of the early imports that still has it's original gray phosphate finish. Later imports that appear to be blued or flat black were refinished before being imported. Of course there is nothing wrong with the refurbed guns. However if you are a purist and/or a collector then the real deal in it's original "as issued" condition might be more desirable.

I took this particular pistol on trade recently and it is in absolutely excellent shape with only the slightest wear around the muzzle from being holstered. I rate it an easy 95%+ gun. The grips are the original brown Bakelite and they not chipped or cracked. Then the bore is bright and in great shape which is important since many of these pistols have dark or worse bores from the corrosive ammo they used.

Pistol comes with 2 magazines one of which is original to the pistol with the same gray phosphate finish. The other is a brand new blued model that's never had a round loaded in it. There is also an original cleaning rod, and a real CZ52 green nylon rope lanyard plus an operators manual printed in English.

Additionally there is an early original holster that is somewhat unusual because it's made of pig skin. It's in very good condition without any tears or bad stitches. The majority of the CZ52 holsters you'll see are light colored leather. So the pig skin version is another feature that collectors favor. You probably can't see this well from the photos because my iPad lacks the resolution to capture such fine details but it's very obviously pig skin when you see it in person.

Price is $350.00. FTF only picked up in the Brandon area. Buyer must be a Florida resident at least 21 years old.

I also have a collection of 252 rounds of 7.62x25 ammo as described below that I will sell to the buyer of this pistol only for an additional $70 which works out to less than $.30 a round

50 round box PPU commercial FMJ non-corrosive
50 round box S&B commercial FMJ non-corrosive
72 round box Romanian Military FMJ, steel inner jacket/magnetic, corrosive primed
(5) 16 round bundles Bulgarian Military, FMJ, steel inner jacket/magnetic, corrosive primed

Thanks for looking

postcontent:
This is a 4” Stainless Steel revolver, per lock made in the early 90’s. This is a copy of the S&W Model 686 (S&W and Taurus were owned by the same company at one time).

In 1970 Smith & Wesson had been purchased by a conglomerate named Bangor Punta. Bangor Punta also purchased 54% of Taurus. Thus, the two companies became "sisters". Smith & Wesson never owned Taurus. They were both independent companies. However, during the next seven years, a great deal of technology, methodology, machinery and tooling were passed between the two. So many Taurus models are actually S&W’s made on Brazil on Smith machinery and with Smith tooling.

title: For Sale/Trade:  VERY RARE.  First year 1913 General Patton Cavalry Sabre
postcontent:
After doing some research on my cutlass I realized how rare this is.  This is the first year production (1913) Springfield Armory "Patton" Cavalry Sabre.  Not many of these have survived the years ESPECIALLY from 1913. Serial Number 3367.  This would be a great cutlass to add to any collection.  Shows minor signs of surface rust as to be expected but in overall good condition.

The cavalry saber, Model 1913, was the last saber issued to and used by the U.S. Cavalry. The designer of the "last of the bright blades" was Lieutenant George S. Patton, Jr. At the time of the redesign, Patton was "Master of the Sword at the Mounted Service School" at Fort Riley, Kansas. Quite an honor for a young Army Lieutenant. Because of his involvement with and enthusiasm for the cavalry saber Patton was given the first of many nicknames, "Saber George."

You may find these from later years for around $400- $600.  The only other 1913 I have seen was in worse condition and went for $1000.  I'm Asking for $800 cash or $1000 in trade value.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Civil War Relic
location: North East of Elkhart, Indiana, United States
postcontent:
Authentic civil war cavalry officer's saber made by Henry Boker of Solingen Germany, who was a blade maker during the civil war, and was known to make swords for both the north and the south. It is of a fairly rare maker mark. Herman Boker (Henry's brother) was the founder of "Boker & Co." Cutlery in New York and imported his brother's swords in support of the civil war. Boker Cutlery is still around today. 

There are some condition issues with the sword, but damn, it's a battle saber and had a rough life ya think? ;) The Pommel needs to be re-peened. These are prized in any condition. It is "presentable" and would look great on display, or in your collection. 

Not cash motivated, but you are welcome to make offers. I will ship to your location.

title: For Sale:  Walther 9mm  P-38 Package (Trade for??)
postcontent:
Own a piece of history. Complete package with manual, holster and 2 magazines.

This is a Walther P-38 9mm that is hard chromed. The gun is in excellent condition, I would say 90%.

There were three companies manufacturing these during WWII - Walther,  Mauser and Spreewerke. 

The serial numbers on this gun are distinct and all match. The wartime code on the gun is AC44 which designates it was made by the Walther company in 1944. The serial number is 327 J which says it was the 327th gun made in the 10th month as the " J"  refers to month of manufacture. It has all the Waffenamt Proof marks consistent with the Walther Company. The original 8 round mag has the WaA135 with eagle which says it was made in the Mauser  factory for Walther Miltary in the 1940's (These original  mags by the way sell individually for $200 to $250). 

There is also a after-market 8 round blued magazine as 2nd mag.

The holster I believe is reproduction and is essentially brand new but has the stamp "Otto Sindel, Berlin, 1938" with Swastika and WaA91. Also stamped P-38.

Call or text Jim at REDACTED or email at REDACTED
